 ancient articulation of emotion, though the ancient Greeks, much like eighteenth-century European societies, often failed to live up to those values. Merging the history of ideas with cultural history, Sternberg examines literary themes upholding empathy and human dignity from Thucydides’s and Xenophon’s histories to Voltaire’s Candide, and from Greek tragic drama to the eighteenth-century novel. She describes shared impacts of the trauma of war, the appeal to reason, and the public acceptance of emotion that encouraged the birth and rebirth of humane values.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCivilization, ClassicalxPhilosophy. 0aCompassionxPhilosophyxHistory. 0aEmpathyxPhilosophyxHistory. 0aEnlightenmentxPhilosophy. 0aHuman rightsxPhilosophyxHistory. 0aIntellectual lifexHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ahuman rights, Ancient Greece, Classical Athens, Ancient Greeks, ancient greek philosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074527640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32291840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477322925423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477322925/original  a978-3-11-074527-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075408-7  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_HICS